ystemd unit active\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:296:# Phase 3: Ollama install + dual-socket systemd units\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:300:    phase \"3/13 — Ollama + dual-socket systemd units\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:310:    # Disable the default service — we manage our own NUMA-pinned units\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:311:    if systemctl list-unit-files | grep -q '^ollama.service'; then\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:312:        log \"Disabling default ollama.service...\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:313:        sudo systemctl disable --now ollama.service 2>/dev/null || true\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:314:        ok \"Default service disabled\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:326:    log \"Writing ollama-0.service (NUMA 0, port ${OLLAMA_PORT_0})...\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:327:    sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/ollama-0.service > /dev/null <<UNIT\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:353:        log \"Writing ollama-1.service (NUMA 1, port ${OLLAMA_PORT_1})...\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:354:        sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/ollama-1.service > /dev/null <<UNIT\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:357:After=network-online.target ollama-0.service\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:379:        warn \"Skipping ollama-1.service — no NUMA node 1 detected\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:383:    sudo systemctl enable --now ollama-0.service\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:384:    [[ -n \"$node1_cpus\" ]] && sudo systemctl enable --now ollama-1.service\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:428:    if systemctl is-active ollama-1.service &>/dev/null; then\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:698:# Phase 11: systemd services for PromptClaw\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:701:phase_systemd() {\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:702:    phase \"11/13 — PromptClaw systemd services\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:704:    log \"Writing promptclaw-bootstrap.service...\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:705:    sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/promptclaw-bootstrap.service > /dev/null <<UNIT\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:721:    log \"Writing promptclaw-daemon.service...\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:722:    sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/promptclaw-daemon.service > /dev/null <<UNIT\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:725:After=network-online.target ollama-0.service promptclaw-datastore.service\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:726:Wants=ollama-0.service promptclaw-datastore.service\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:750:    log \"Writing promptclaw-sdp-runner.service...\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:751:    sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/promptclaw-sdp-runner.service > /dev/null <<UNIT\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:754:After=promptclaw-bootstrap.service promptclaw-daemon.service\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:755:Requires=promptclaw-bootstrap.service\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:781:    sudo systemctl enable promptclaw-bootstrap.service\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:782:    sudo systemctl enable promptclaw-daemon.service\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:783:    sudo systemctl enable promptclaw-sdp-runner.service\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:784:    ok \"systemd units installed and enabled\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:792:    phase \"12/13 — Starting PromptClaw services\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:795:    sudo systemctl start promptclaw-bootstrap.service\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:799:    sudo systemctl start promptclaw-daemon.service || warn \"Daemon start returned non-zero\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:801:    if systemctl is-active promptclaw-daemon.service &>/dev/null; then\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:808:    sudo systemctl start promptclaw-sdp-runner.service || warn \"SDP runner start returned non-zero\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:810:    if systemctl is-active promptclaw-sdp-runner.service &>/dev/null; then\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:830:    log \"Checking services...\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:832:        if systemctl is-active \"${svc}.service\" &>/dev/null; then\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:840:    if systemctl list-unit-files | grep -q '^ollama-1.service'; then\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:841:        if systemctl is-active ollama-1.service &>/dev/null; then\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:910:        echo \"  - sudo systemctl restart promptclaw-daemon.service\"\n++deploy/r750/install.sh:948:    should_run_phase \"systemd\"    && phase_systemd\n++docs/command-reference.md:103:- child CLI processes spawned by the live daemon run without inherited systemd watchdog variables\n++docs/command-reference.md:151:- `my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-bootstrap.service`\n++docs/command-reference.md:152:- `my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service`\n++docs/command-reference.md:164:This probe is platform-aware: it checks `launchctl` on macOS homes and `systemctl` on Linux homes so status checks do not crash when the local service manager is absent.\n++docs/command-reference.md:232:- `cypherclaw_boot.sh` now also starts `cypherclaw-observer-ollama.service` and launches `observer_vision.py` with `OBSERVER_OLLAMA_URLS=http://127.0.0.1:11435/api/chat,http://127.0.0.1:11434/api/chat`, so the camera summary path uses a dedicated observer queue first and only falls back to the shared local model queue if needed.\n++docs/command-reference.md:234:- `my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-av-stack.service` binds that wrapper to `graphical.target` as `User=user`, so the music and face stack can come back after reboot without an operator SSH session.\n++docs/master-plan-20260409.md:60:- ❌ Restart services unless genuinely broken\n++docs/master-plan-20260409.md:87:- Ollama with dual NUMA-pinned systemd units\n++docs/master-plan-20260409.md:90:- Installs all systemd services, starts everything, verifies\n++docs/handoff-protocol.md:27:Before that preflight runs, the launcher now removes a stale `.sdp/run.lock` when it points at a dead PID. That makes routine systemd restarts self-healing instead of leaving the queue runner in a restart loop.\n++docs/handoff-protocol.md:126:- `my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service` uses `Restart=always` so clean queue-run exits restart automatically; maintenance-gated launcher exits use code `75`, which is marked successful and excluded from restart.\n++docs/handoff-protocol.md:128:For live CypherClaw daemon executions, the transport also records concurrency semaphore transitions (`acquired`, `released`, `rejected`) to Observatory and keeps daemon status probes platform-aware so the same code path can run on macOS launchd and Linux systemd hosts without crashing.\n++docs/handoff-protocol.md:129:The daemon also strips systemd watchdog variables from child-process environments before invoking agents or helper CLIs, so only the daemon main process can send watchdog notifications.\n++docs/handoff-protocol.md:164:There is now a system-level cold-boot handoff for that same stack. `cypherclaw-av-stack.service` can call `cypherclaw_av_boot.sh` at `graphical.target`, and that wrapper re-establishes the same live invariants the manual recovery used: audio first, then composer, then the meter, then room/sampler backfill if needed, plus explicit face/gallery restarts under X so stale display clients do not survive reboot recovery. That wrapper now also exports the user `XDG_RUNTIME_DIR` before launching those display clients, which matters on the live box because SDL/X can stay blank even with `DISPLAY=:0` when the user session runtime dir is missing. It chooses the self-listener backend up front, runs a second delayed dedupe pass so stale late-start copies from other hooks are collapsed back to a single surviving daemon, and `cypherclaw_boot.sh` now delegates core AV ownership to that wrapper instead of racing it with its own copies of the same daemons.\n++docs/sdp-cli-stuck-gemini-report.md:35:### systemd Resource Usage\n++docs/sdp-cli-stuck-gemini-report.md:37:When the service was restarted after 7 hours:\n++docs/sdp-cli-stuck-gemini-report.md:66:- **48.6 GB memory consumed** — risked OOM-killing other CypherClaw services\n++docs/sdp-cli-stuck-gemini-report.md:105:# In the systemd unit or in sdp-cli's subprocess invocation\n++docs/sdp-cli-stuck-gemini-report.md:130:- Pipeline: cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service (bash loop launcher)\n++docs/cypherclaw-musicianship-roadmap.md:20:- `sample_capture_daemon.py`, `sampler_buffers.py`, and `sampler_dispatch.py`\n++docs/cypherclaw-musicianship-roadmap.md:64:- `sample_capture_daemon.py` can capture and tag room/contact material for\n++docs/architecture.md:106:- systemd-managed runner startup through `my-claw/tools/sdp_runner_launcher.sh`\n++docs/architecture.md:116:Daemon child processes also run with a sanitized environment: `NOTIFY_SOCKET`, `WATCHDOG_PID`, and `WATCHDOG_USEC` are stripped before spawning agent CLIs or helper commands, so only the daemon main process talks to systemd's watchdog socket.\n++docs/architecture.md:118:The managed runner path also repairs a stale `.sdp/run.lock` before preflight runs. That keeps normal systemd restarts from failing their own startup checks after the previous runner PID has been terminated.\n++docs/architecture.md:119:The systemd runner unit itself now uses `Restart=always` so a clean `sdp-cli run` exit cannot silently strand the queue. Maintenance-gated launcher exits stay non-looping through `SuccessExitStatus=75` and `RestartPreventExitStatus=75`.\n++docs/architecture.md:154:Cold boot now has a repo-backed AV entrypoint too. `cypherclaw_av_boot.sh` waits for the display, checks whether `scsynth` and `duet_composer.py` are already present from another startup path, and only calls `start_audio.sh` / `restart_composer.sh` if they are still missing. After that it waits for `SuperCollider:out_1`, relaunches `self_listener.py` under a detached session with the explicit verified JACK backend, force-restarts `face_display.py` and `gallery_x11.py` under X, and exports `XDG_RUNTIME_DIR=/run/user/1000` for those display clients so they attach to the real user session instead of restarting into a blank SDL/X state. It only backfills `room_listener.py` and `sample_playback_engine.py` if no other startup path has already brought them up during the same boot. If stale copies from earlier bad boot loops are already present, that wrapper now deduplicates those optional daemons back down to one live process, then runs a second delayed dedupe pass so late-start copies from another boot hook are also collapsed. That wrapper now also normalizes the live dual-head modes after X recovery, using the observed `DP-2` face screen at `1280x1024` and `DP-0` gallery screen at `3840x2160`, and it launches the face on `:0.0` with the gallery on `:0.1` so the 4K gallery is no longer offset into the wrong coordinate space. `cypherclaw_boot.sh` now delegates core audio/composer/face/gallery/room-listener/sample ownership to that wrapper instead of trying to start the same daemons itself. The matching `cypherclaw-av-stack.service` is designed as a system service bound to `graphical.target`, so the live music/face stack can return after reboot even when only the core main daemon unit is already persistent.\n++docs/architecture.md:160:The slow observer summary path is now queue-aware as well. `observer_vision.py` now accepts an ordered `OBSERVER_OLLAMA_URLS` list and the boot path routes it to a dedicated observer queue on `127.0.0.1:11435` before falling back to the shared `11434` instance. A matching `cypherclaw-observer-ollama.service` runs that second queue as the `ollama` user against the shared model store, which keeps camera summaries from competing directly with the main local model traffic. When both endpoints are saturated, the observer no longer writes the raw `HTTP Error 503` text as the room description. Instead it publishes a compact local fallback summary derived from the fast image analysis, records `vision_backend` and `vision_error` in `/tmp/observer_state.json`, and backs off before retrying the slow multimodal call again. That keeps the observer state readable during local-model contention while still leaving the slow summary path available when Ollama is free.\n++my-claw/docs/discovery-report.md:23:- AGENT_CONTEXT — Identity block prepended to all agent calls with full capabilities list, available services, and 8 active PRDs.\n++my-claw/docs/discovery-report.md:32:- `tools/io_guard.sh` — Independent systemd timer (every 30s), kills agents AND sdp-cli at 75% I/O. Sends Telegram alert. Operates independently of the daemon.\n++my-claw/docs/discovery-report.md:34:- `tools/server_health.py` — Health checks (disk, memory, load, zombies, daemon, services, temperature). Auto-maintenance: kills stale agents, cleans temp files, truncates oversized logs.\n++my-claw/docs/discovery-report.md:37:- OPT-003: Unified auto-recovery service checking all services every 5 min (prd-server-optimization.md)\n++my-claw/docs/discovery-report.md:38:- OPT-004: Full boot-resilience — verify all tmpfs dirs, restore DBs, verify services, restart pipeline on boot (prd-server-optimization.md)\n++my-claw/docs/discovery-report.md:57:- `tools/server_health.py` — Periodic health reflection (disk, memory, load, services) with auto-maintenance actions.\n++docs/discovery_20260329_095247.md:158:│       ├── boot_hardening.service  # Systemd unit for boot hardening\n++docs/discovery_20260329_095247.md:173:│       │   ├── systemd/            # Service file for auto-launch\n++docs/discovery_20260329_095247.md:409:**Remote server (CypherClaw) services:**\n++docs/discovery_20260329_095247.md:471:- `systemd/` — Service file for auto-launch on boot\n++my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-av-stack.service:3:After=display-manager.service network-online.target sound.target\n++docs/r750-model-evaluation-plan.md:409:A Python function receives a list of FortiGate firewall rules. Each rule is a dict with keys: id, src, dst, service, action. Write a function that returns all rules where action is \"accept\" and either src or dst contains \"10.10.100.0/24\". Include type hints.\n++docs/r750-model-evaluation-plan.md:413:    {\"id\": 1, \"src\": \"10.10.100.0/24\", \"dst\": \"0.0.0.0/0\", \"service\": \"HTTPS\", \"action\": \"accept\"},\n++docs/r750-model-evaluation-plan.md:414:    {\"id\": 2, \"src\": \"10.10.200.0/24\", \"dst\": \"10.10.100.0/24\", \"service\": \"SSH\", \"action\": \"deny\"},\n++docs/r750-model-evaluation-plan.md:415:    {\"id\": 3, \"src\": \"any\", \"dst\": \"10.10.100.5/32\", \"service\": \"ICMP\", \"action\": \"accept\"},\n++docs/r750-model-evaluation-plan.md:416:    {\"id\": 4, \"src\": \"10.10.100.0/24\", \"dst\": \"10.10.200.0/24\", \"service\": \"ANY\", \"action\": \"deny\"},\n++docs/r750-model-evaluation-plan.md:800:- Are the SD-WAN service rules that reference these members included?\n++docs/2026-03-28-promptclaw-discovery-phase2-report-CODEX.md:105:- `systemctl status ollama` showed `/etc/systemd/system/ollama.service` active since `Fri 2026-03-27 23:29:44 UTC`.\n++docs/2026-03-28-promptclaw-discovery-phase2-report-CODEX.md:109:- `ollama ps` was empty at the final check, so the service is running but no model was currently resident after the benchmark completed.\n++docs/2026-03-28-promptclaw-discovery-phase2-report-CODEX.md:378:**F4 — Systemd Unit Inventory:** The live runtime is service-driven, with tmpfs mounted by systemd and I/O protection on a timer.\n++docs/2026-03-28-promptclaw-discovery-phase2-report-CODEX.md:380:- `/etc/systemd/system/cypherclaw.service`\n++docs/2026-03-28-promptclaw-discovery-phase2-report-CODEX.md:389:- `/etc/systemd/system/io-guard.timer`\n++docs/2026-03-28-promptclaw-discovery-phase2-report-CODEX.md:392:  - triggers `/etc/systemd/system/io-guard.service`\n++docs/2026-03-28-promptclaw-discovery-phase2-report-CODEX.md:393:- `/etc/systemd/system/io-guard.service`\n++docs/2026-03-28-promptclaw-discovery-phase2-report-CODEX.md:396:  - an earlier `systemctl list-units --all` snapshot showed `failed`, so this service has recently changed state\n++docs/2026-03-28-promptclaw-discovery-phase2-report-CODEX.md:413:3. Standardize the runtime Python target for RAG work, then install the vector stack there: either keep using `/usr/bin/python3` for `cypherclaw.service` or move the service to `/home/user/cypherclaw/.venv`, then pull `nomic-embed-text` and install one vector backend in that same interpreter.\n++my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-observer-ollama.service:3:After=network-online.target ollama.service\n++docs/cypherclaw-sampler-architecture.md:42:| `my-claw/tools/sample_capture_daemon.py` | Long-running capture process. Maintains 60-second JACK ring buffers for the contact mic, room mic, and the SuperCollider self bus. Hosts the `InterestingMomentDetector`, the `AcousticFeatures` analyzer, the contextual+acoustic tagger (`build_sample_tags`), the `SampleIndex` SQLite persistence layer, the `save_capture` write path, and the post-song `self_quote()` hook. |\n++docs/cypherclaw-sampler-architecture.md:43:| `my-claw/tools/sample_capture_verify.py` | Deterministic smoke verifier. Synthesizes a known room sound, drives `save_capture`, and asserts the descriptor lands in `index.sqlite` with the expected context and acoustic tags. Used to sanity-check the capture pipeline without requiring live audio hardware. |\n++docs/cypherclaw-sampler-architecture.md:64:   at 48 kHz inside `sample_capture_daemon.py`. The\n++docs/startup-wizard.md:83:- The same live daemon toolchain is now portable across the MacBook and Linux server homes, so post-init status and runner checks do not assume one service manager or one repo layout.\n++docs/startup-wizard.md:84:- In the Linux server home, child CLIs launched by the daemon no longer inherit systemd watchdog variables, so helper processes do not generate spurious `Got notification message from PID ...` journal noise.\n++docs/startup-wizard.md:85:- The managed runner now also clears a stale `.sdp/run.lock` before preflight, so normal service restarts do not get stuck behind a dead PID from the previous runner process.\n++docs/startup-wizard.md:141:- For cold boots, the repo now ships `cypherclaw_av_boot.sh` plus `my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-av-stack.service`. That service is intended to be enabled at `graphical.target` and re-establishes the live AV stack after reboot by calling the hardened audio/composer scripts only when the core stack is still missing, waiting for `SuperCollider:out_1`, relaunching the self-listener on the verified JACK path, force-restarting the face and gallery displays under X with the user runtime dir exported, and deduplicating/backfilling the room listener and sampler so another startup path cannot leave stale late-arriving copies behind. The wrapper now also reapplies the live dual-head geometry after X recovery, keeping the face on `:0.0` / `DP-2` at `1280x1024` and the gallery on `:0.1` / `DP-0` at `3840x2160`. `cypherclaw_boot.sh` now delegates core AV ownership to that wrapper instead of starting overlapping copies of the same daemons itself.\n++docs/startup-wizard.md:144:- The observer path now prefers a dedicated local Ollama queue on `127.0.0.1:11435` through `cypherclaw-observer-ollama.service`, with the shared `11434` queue as fallback. If both are saturated, `observer_vision.py` still stays readable instead of surfacing the raw HTTP error: it emits a short local fallback description, records `vision_backend` / `vision_error` in `/tmp/observer_state.json`, and waits before retrying the slow multimodal call.\n++my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-bootstrap.service:4:Before=cypherclaw.service cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service\n++my-claw/scripts/cypherclaw_boot.sh:3:# Run from /etc/rc.local or a systemd service as user\n++my-claw/scripts/cypherclaw_boot.sh:33:ensure_observer_ollama_service() {\n++my-claw/scripts/cypherclaw_boot.sh:34:    sudo -n systemctl start cypherclaw-observer-ollama.service 2>/dev/null || true\n++my-claw/scripts/cypherclaw_boot.sh:81:ensure_observer_ollama_service\n++my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service:3:After=cypherclaw-bootstrap.service cypherclaw.service network-online.target\n++my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service:4:Requires=cypherclaw-bootstrap.service\n++docs/sdp-cli-findings-report.md:29:- systemd-managed runner hot-looped at 10s intervals, restart counter reached **5007** in ~14 hours\n++docs/sdp-cli-findings-report.md:30:- `orchestrate` command exited 0 when blocked, making systemd see \"success\"\n++docs/sdp-cli-findings-report.md:202:The default systemd unit shipped with sdp-cli templates (and used on both CypherClaw and likely CTTickets) executes:\n++docs/sdp-cli-findings-report.md:212:Update the systemd unit template in the sdp-cli project scaffold:\n++docs/sdp-cli-findings-report.md:222:And add to the sdp-cli docs: \"For unattended systemd-managed runners, use `sdp-cli run`. Reserve `orchestrate` for interactive use where a human watches the output.\"\n++docs/sdp-cli-findings-report.md:238:1. **Immediately:** Update default systemd launcher template (trivial, prevents future Bug 1 incidents).\n++docs/coherence-foundations.md:91:- **Governance-as-a-Service (GaaS, Gaurav et al., 2025).** GaaS demonstrates that governance rules can be evaluated as a service layer with 95% precision and 90% recall, without requiring changes to the governed agents. The key insight is separation of concerns: the agent produces output, and a separate system evaluates compliance.\n++docs/coherence-foundations.md:247:- **Rationale:** Reduces infrastructure to a single service\n++my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-image-api.service:4:After=network-online.target cypherclaw-jack.service\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:10:#   1. systemd unit `cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service` is not active\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:78:# Check 1: systemd unit active\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:80:check_systemd_active() {\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:81:    if systemctl is-active cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service &>/dev/null; then\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:82:        ok \"systemd_inactive\"\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:85:    local state=$(systemctl show -p ActiveState --value cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service 2>/dev/null || echo unknown)\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:86:    alert \"systemd_inactive\" \"cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service is not active (state=${state})\"\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:98:    # The process might be briefly gone between runs — only alert if systemd is also unhappy\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:99:    if ! systemctl is-active cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service &>/dev/null; then\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:100:        alert \"process_missing\" \"No sdp-cli process running and systemd unit not active\"\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:171:# Check 5: systemd hot-loop detection\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:174:    # Count systemd restart events in the last hour\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:177:        restart_count=$(journalctl -u cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service \\\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:192:        \"systemd has restarted cypherclaw-sdp-runner ${restart_count} times in the last hour. Hot-loop detected.\"\n++my-claw/scripts/sdp_watchdog.sh:204:    check_systemd_active || ((failures++))\n++tests/test_healthcheck_script_runtime.py:155:def test_healthcheck_defaults_cover_module_daemon_and_systemd_log(tmp_path: Path) -> None:\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:365:### 3.1 Main daemon service\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:368:sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/cypherclaw.service << 'UNIT'\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:372:After=network-online.target ollama-0.service ollama-1.service docker-datastore.service\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:373:Wants=network-online.target ollama-0.service ollama-1.service\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:404:### 3.2 SDP runner service\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:407:sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service << 'UNIT'\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:410:After=cypherclaw-bootstrap.service cypherclaw.service network-online.target\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:411:Requires=cypherclaw-bootstrap.service\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:441:### 3.3 Web platform service\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:444:sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/cypherclaw-web.service << 'UNIT'\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:447:After=network-online.target docker-datastore.service cypherclaw.service\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:475:### 3.4 Bootstrap service (tmpfs initialization)\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:478:sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/cypherclaw-bootstrap.service << 'UNIT'\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:496:### 3.5 Gallery service (GlyphWeave art display)\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:499:sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/cypherclaw-gallery.service << 'UNIT'\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:502:After=ollama-0.service cypherclaw.service\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:503:Wants=ollama-0.service\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:522:### 3.6 Enable all services\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:534:1. docker-datastore.service    → PostgreSQL + Redis containers\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:535:2. ollama-0.service            → NUMA socket 0 (port 11434)\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:536:3. ollama-1.service            → NUMA socket 1 (port 11435)\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:537:4. ollama-warmup.service       → Preload models into RAM\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:538:5. cypherclaw-bootstrap.service → tmpfs workspace init\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:539:6. cypherclaw.service          → Main daemon (Telegram bot)\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:540:7. cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service → SDP task runner\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:541:8. cypherclaw-web.service      → FastAPI dashboard\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:542:9. cypherclaw-gallery.service  → Art display\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:642:2. Stop `cypherclaw.service` on CypherClaw (but keep Ollama + gallery running for art)\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:801:| 5 | Create systemd services | Day 10 | Step 4 |\n++docs/r750-application-deployment-plan.md:803:| 7 | Start services, verify | Day 10 | Step 6 |\n++docs/cypherclaw-emsd-roadmap.md:155:  - key/mode detection and similarity ranking as reusable services\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:612:This installs the `ollama` binary to `/usr/local/bin/ollama` and creates a systemd service. **Disable the default service** — you are going to run two custom ones:\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:641:Create the service file:\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:644:sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/ollama-0.service << 'UNIT'\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:679:sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/ollama-1.service << 'UNIT'\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:836:Create a systemd service for the warmup:\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:839:sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/ollama-warmup.service << 'UNIT'\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:842:After=ollama-0.service ollama-1.service\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:843:Requires=ollama-0.service ollama-1.service\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:874:services:\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:929:> **Note on binding:** Both services bind to `127.0.0.1` only — they are not exposed to the network. Access from other machines should go through Tailscale and an SSH tunnel, or you can later change the bind address to the Tailscale IP (100.x.x.x) if needed.\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:1062:sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/docker-datastore.service << 'UNIT'\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:1065:Requires=docker.service\n++docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:1066:After=docker.service\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:1778:### Relevant systemd services\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:1780:$ systemctl list-units --type=service --state=running 2>/dev/null | grep -iE \"promptclaw|glyphweave|ollama|redis|postgres|chroma|nginx|uvicorn|gunicorn\"\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:1781:  nginx.service               loaded active running A high performance web server and a reverse proxy server\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:1782:  ollama.service              loaded active running Ollama Service\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:1783:  postgresql@16-main.service  loaded active running PostgreSQL Cluster 16-main\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:1784:  redis-server.service        loaded active running Advanced key-value store\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3483:| GW-008 | Create the gallery web server at `tools/art_gallery/` using FastAPI + HTMX + Jinja2 templates. Pages: (1) Gallery grid — all artworks as thumbnails with composite score overlay, filterable by model, art_type, score range, date, pet, theme; sortable by score, date, recency. (2) Artwork detail — full-size render, text version in code block, AEAF player for animations, generation stats (model, effort, time, retries), assessment scores radar chart, qualitative feedback. (3) Experiment dashboard — calibration progress, model leaderboard table, score distributions per model (box plots), generation time comparison, success rate heatmap (model × art_type). (4) Live canvas — prompt input, model/effort/size/palette selectors, generate button, real-time status, result display with scores. (5) Remix — take existing artwork, modify parameters, regenerate. Serve static files (rendered PNGs) from disk. Run as a systemd service on port 8080, accessible via Tailscale. | MUST | T3 | - Gallery grid loads with thumbnail images and scores<br/>- Filtering by model, art_type, score, date works<br/>- Detail page shows PNG, text, scores, generation stats<br/>- AEAF animations play in browser (JS frame player)<br/>- Experiment dashboard shows calibration progress and leaderboard<br/>- Live canvas generates art on demand and displays result<br/>- Remix modifies parameters and regenerates<br/>- Server runs on port 8080 as systemd service |\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3492:| GW-017 | Create a systemd service for the gallery web server at `/etc/systemd/system/cypherclaw-gallery.service`. The service should: run as user `user`, start after postgresql and cypherclaw services, use the same TMPDIR and environment as the daemon, restart on failure with 10-second delay, bind to port 8080. Add an Nginx reverse proxy config to serve the gallery at a clean URL if Nginx is available. | SHOULD | T1 | - Service file created and enabled<br/>- Gallery starts on boot after postgresql<br/>- Gallery accessible at cypherclaw:8080<br/>- Service restarts automatically on crash<br/>- Logs go to journalctl |\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3794:| GW-008 | Create the gallery web server at `tools/art_gallery/` using FastAPI + HTMX + Jinja2 templates. Pages: (1) Gallery grid — all artworks as thumbnails with composite score overlay, filterable by model, art_type, score range, date, pet, theme; sortable by score, date, recency. (2) Artwork detail — full-size render, text version in code block, AEAF player for animations, generation stats (model, effort, time, retries), assessment scores radar chart, qualitative feedback. (3) Experiment dashboard — calibration progress, model leaderboard table, score distributions per model (box plots), generation time comparison, success rate heatmap (model × art_type). (4) Live canvas — prompt input, model/effort/size/palette selectors, generate button, real-time status, result display with scores. (5) Remix — take existing artwork, modify parameters, regenerate. Serve static files (rendered PNGs) from disk. Run as a systemd service on port 8080, accessible via Tailscale. | MUST | T3 | - Gallery grid loads with thumbnail images and scores<br/>- Filtering by model, art_type, score, date works<br/>- Detail page shows PNG, text, scores, generation stats<br/>- AEAF animations play in browser (JS frame player)<br/>- Experiment dashboard shows calibration progress and leaderboard<br/>- Live canvas generates art on demand and displays result<br/>- Remix modifies parameters and regenerates<br/>- Server runs on port 8080 as systemd service |\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3803:| GW-017 | Create a systemd service for the gallery web server at `/etc/systemd/system/cypherclaw-gallery.service`. The service should: run as user `user`, start after postgresql and cypherclaw services, use the same TMPDIR and environment as the daemon, restart on failure with 10-second delay, bind to port 8080. Add an Nginx reverse proxy config to serve the gallery at a clean URL if Nginx is available. | SHOULD | T1 | - Service file created and enabled<br/>- Gallery starts on boot after postgresql<br/>- Gallery accessible at cypherclaw:8080<br/>- Service restarts automatically on crash<br/>- Logs go to journalctl |\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:4110:| GW-008 | Create the gallery web server at `tools/art_gallery/` using FastAPI + HTMX + Jinja2 templates. Pages: (1) Gallery grid — all artworks as thumbnails with composite score overlay, filterable by model, art_type, score range, date, pet, theme; sortable by score, date, recency. (2) Artwork detail — full-size render, text version in code block, AEAF player for animations, generation stats (model, effort, time, retries), assessment scores radar chart, qualitative feedback. (3) Experiment dashboard — calibration progress, model leaderboard table, score distributions per model (box plots), generation time comparison, success rate heatmap (model × art_type). (4) Live canvas — prompt input, model/effort/size/palette selectors, generate button, real-time status, result display with scores. (5) Remix — take existing artwork, modify parameters, regenerate. Serve static files (rendered PNGs) from disk. Run as a systemd service on port 8080, accessible via Tailscale. | MUST | T3 | - Gallery grid loads with thumbnail images and scores<br/>- Filtering by model, art_type, score, date works<br/>- Detail page shows PNG, text, scores, generation stats<br/>- AEAF animations play in browser (JS frame player)<br/>- Experiment dashboard shows calibration progress and leaderboard<br/>- Live canvas generates art on demand and displays result<br/>- Remix modifies parameters and regenerates<br/>- Server runs on port 8080 as systemd service |\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:4119:| GW-017 | Create a systemd service for the gallery web server at `/etc/systemd/system/cypherclaw-gallery.service`. The service should: run as user `user`, start after postgresql and cypherclaw services, use the same TMPDIR and environment as the daemon, restart on failure with 10-second delay, bind to port 8080. Add an Nginx reverse proxy config to serve the gallery at a clean URL if Nginx is available. | SHOULD | T1 | - Service file created and enabled<br/>- Gallery starts on boot after postgresql<br/>- Gallery accessible at cypherclaw:8080<br/>- Service restarts automatically on crash<br/>- Logs go to journalctl |\n++docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:5124:   - Immediate work can build on the existing Python daemon/service environment, Redis, SQLite observatory/state, the existing GlyphWeave DSL/scenes/player modules, and the multi-agent orchestration already present in the repository.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-server-optimization.md:5:CypherClaw's home server (Intel i5-10505, 64GB DDR4, 1.8TB SSD) is using <5% of its capacity. This PRD addresses the remaining optimizations to fully utilize the server's resources: expanding Redis usage, enabling sdp-cli concurrency, setting up auto-recovery systems, and ensuring all services are resilient to reboots and failures.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-server-optimization.md:32:| OPT-003 | Create a unified auto-recovery service. When any critical service fails, automatically recover: (a) sdp-cli pipeline — if not running and circuit breaker is closed, restart with ionice/nice from tmpfs workdir, (b) Ollama — if not responding, restart via systemctl, (c) daemon — already handled by systemd, but add pre-start hook to ensure tmpfs dirs exist, (d) Redis — monitor and restart. Create `tools/auto_recover.sh` that runs every 5 minutes via systemd timer, checking all services and restarting as needed. Send Telegram alert on any recovery action. | MUST | T2 | - Auto-recovery script checks: daemon, sdp-cli, Ollama, Redis, PostgreSQL<br/>- Restarts failed services automatically<br/>- Sends Telegram alert on recovery<br/>- Runs every 5 minutes via systemd timer<br/>- Logs all actions to tmpfs |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-server-optimization.md:33:| OPT-004 | Make the daemon fully reboot-resilient. On startup, the daemon should: (a) ensure all tmpfs dirs exist (call init_workdir.sh if needed), (b) restore state.db from backup if tmpfs copy is missing, (c) verify Observatory DB exists, (d) verify Ollama is running, (e) verify Redis is running, (f) check if sdp-cli pipeline should be restarted (was it running before reboot?). Add a `_boot_recovery()` function called at the start of `poll_loop()`. | MUST | T2 | - Daemon starts cleanly after any reboot<br/>- No crash loops from missing tmpfs files<br/>- State restored from backup automatically<br/>- All services verified on startup<br/>- sdp-cli restarted if it was running before reboot |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-server-optimization.md:35:| OPT-006 | Set up Nginx reverse proxy for internal services. Configure Nginx to serve: (a) gallery at `cypherclaw:8080` → localhost:8080, (b) Ollama API at `cypherclaw:11434` → localhost:11434, (c) a simple status page at `cypherclaw:80` showing server health, service status, and pipeline progress as static HTML refreshed every minute. All accessible via Tailscale only. | SHOULD | T2 | - Nginx proxies to gallery and Ollama<br/>- Status page at port 80 with auto-refresh<br/>- Only accessible via Tailscale (bind to tailscale0 or use allow/deny)<br/>- SSL not required (internal only) |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-server-optimization.md:36:| OPT-007 | Implement sdp-cli pipeline auto-restart. When the I/O guard kills the pipeline, or the pipeline exits due to escalation/circuit breaker, automatically restart it after a 5-minute cooldown. The auto-recovery service (OPT-003) should: detect pipeline not running, check circuit breaker state, reset if needed, and restart from the tmpfs working copy. Track restart count — if more than 3 restarts in an hour, stop and alert Anthony. | MUST | T2 | - Pipeline auto-restarts after I/O guard kill<br/>- 5-minute cooldown between restarts<br/>- Circuit breaker auto-reset on restart<br/>- Max 3 restarts per hour before giving up<br/>- Telegram alert on each restart and on give-up |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-server-optimization.md:38:| OPT-009 | Create a server status dashboard as a simple HTML page. Generate a static HTML file every 60 seconds at `/var/www/html/index.html` showing: server vitals (CPU, RAM, I/O, load), service status (daemon, sdp-cli, Ollama, Redis, PostgreSQL), pipeline progress (tasks complete/total, ETA), pet status (all 4 pets with class and level), recent events (last 10 Observatory entries). Use a systemd timer to regenerate. Served by Nginx at port 80. | SHOULD | T2 | - HTML dashboard generated every 60s<br/>- Shows all vitals, services, pipeline, pets<br/>- Accessible at cypherclaw:80 via Tailscale<br/>- Auto-refreshes in browser<br/>- Works without JavaScript (pure HTML/CSS) |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-server-optimization.md:39:| OPT-010 | Set up tmpfs working copy validation. Before starting the sdp-cli pipeline, verify the tmpfs working copy is valid: (a) .git directory exists, (b) remote points to disk repo, (c) state.db exists and is valid SQLite, (d) sdp.toml symlink is valid, (e) AGENTS.md and pyproject.toml exist. If any check fails, re-initialize from disk. Add this as a pre-check in the auto-recovery service. | MUST | T1 | - Validation checks all 5 conditions<br/>- Auto-reinitializes from disk on failure<br/>- Runs before every pipeline start<br/>- Logged to tmpfs |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-server-optimization.md:53:Redis expansion, Nginx proxy. Better caching and service access.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-server-optimization.md:62:| Service recovery | All services back within 5 minutes of failure |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:16:- **Critical changes**: full system health scan (all imports, gates, services, logs)\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:20:This pattern applies at every level: conversation agents, sdp-cli pipeline agents, the daemon, and this Introspector service. The Introspector is the autonomous embodiment of this loop — running 24/7 without human intervention.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:24:A separate always-on service (`tools/introspector.py`) that continuously monitors all system logs and data sources, detects error patterns, autonomously diagnoses and fixes issues using a generate/verify/fix cycle with cross-provider agent verification, and reports activity via tiered Telegram notifications. The introspector is CypherClaw's immune system — it watches everything, learns from patterns, and heals proactively.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:46:1. **All 8 data sources** — daemon log, pipeline log, I/O guard log, event stream, watchdog log, Observatory DB, health check output, systemd journal\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:48:3. **Separate systemd service** — independent from the daemon. Can diagnose daemon issues, restart independently, run at its own pace.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:55:tools/introspector.py          # Main service — systemd managed\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:80:| DS-8 | Systemd journal | `journalctl` | 5 min | OOM kills, service crashes, kernel errors |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:86:| IN-001 | Create `tools/introspector.py` as a standalone service with main loop. Scan all 8 data sources at their configured intervals. Track last-read position per source to avoid re-processing. Run as systemd service with auto-restart. | T1 |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:91:| IN-006 | Create `introspector/reporter.py` — tiered Telegram notifications. Critical (service down, data corruption, security): send immediately. Fix applied: send short message (\"Fixed: [description]\"). Pattern analysis + trends: weekly digest (Sunday morning). All messages under 300 chars except weekly digest. | T1 |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-introspector.md:92:| IN-007 | Create systemd service file `introspector.service`. Runs as user service, auto-restart on failure, depends on redis and cypherclaw-daemon. Wrap in I/O protection (ionice -c3 nice -n19). Start after daemon. | T1 |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:46:**Phase 3 — Live capture daemon (CCS-015..CCS-021).** `sample_capture_daemon.py` maintains rolling 60-second buffers of contact mic + room mic via JACK input; an interesting-moment detector flags acoustically novel windows; flagged windows get saved to `samples/contact/` or `samples/room/` with auto-generated tags (arc phase, mood, time, who-is-in-room, acoustic features); systemd unit keeps the daemon running. End of phase: leaving the daemon running for an hour produces ~10–30 tagged WAV files representing the room's acoustic life.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:59:- Live JACK capture path — contact mic on `system:capture_FL` and room mic on `system:capture_FR` (Scarlett inputs already wired via `cypherclaw-jack.service`).\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:66:- **New** `my-claw/tools/sample_capture_daemon.py` — rolling-buffer + interesting-moment detector + auto-tagger\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:67:- **New** `my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-sample-capture.service` — keeps the daemon alive across reboots\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:69:- **New** `my-claw/tests/test_sample_capture_daemon.py` — interesting-moment detector against canned audio\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:103:| CCS-015 | Implement `sample_capture_daemon.py` rolling 60-second buffers reading from `system:capture_1` (contact mic) and `system:capture_2` (room mic) via JACK. | MUST | T1 | - daemon opens two JACK ports `cypherclaw-capture:in_contact` and `cypherclaw-capture:in_room`<br/>- each maintains a 60-second numpy ring buffer at 48 kHz<br/>- exposes `get_window(source, duration_sec, offset_sec) -> np.ndarray` for the moment-detector to pull recent windows<br/>- handles JACK xruns gracefully (logs, does not crash)<br/>- tests with a synthetic JACK input fixture verify ring-buffer correctness, window extraction, and xrun recovery |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:104:| CCS-016 | Implement interesting-moment detector: novelty (spectral flux) + transient density + RMS thresholds + duration-min/max gating. | MUST | T1 | - `sample_capture_daemon.py::InterestingMomentDetector` pulls 1-second windows every 250 ms<br/>- flags a window when: `spectral_flux > 0.6 * recent_median` AND `rms > -45 dBFS` AND `transient_count >= 2` AND `since_last_capture > 30 sec`<br/>- on flag, expands to a 4–8 second window centered on the flagged sub-window (length proportional to spectral richness)<br/>- thresholds are tunable via env / config<br/>- tests with canned audio fixtures (silence, footsteps, dishwasher hum, music) verify expected flag/no-flag for each |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:105:| CCS-017 | Auto-tag captured samples: arc phase, mood, presence, time-of-day, plus heuristic acoustic tags (warm if low spectral centroid, metallic if high+narrow band, transient if high transient density, etc.). | MUST | T1 | - `sample_capture_daemon.py::auto_tag(window, context) -> dict` returns a dict mergeable into `SampleRecord`<br/>- arc_phase / mood / presence pulled from `/tmp/organism_state.json` and `/tmp/room_presence.json`<br/>- character tags derived from heuristics: spectral_centroid<800Hz → \"warm\"; narrow-band high-centroid → \"metallic\"; sustained_amplitude_ratio>0.7 → \"sustained\"; transient_density>3/sec → \"percussive\"; pitch_confidence>0.7 → \"harmonic\"; etc.<br/>- tests verify each heuristic against canned fixtures and that the merged record validates against `SampleRecord` schema |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:106:| CCS-018 | Captured samples land in `samples/contact/` or `samples/room/` as 24-bit 48 kHz WAV with metadata-tagged filename and an entry in `index.sqlite`. | MUST | T1 | - `sample_capture_daemon.py::save_capture(window, source, tags) -> SampleRecord` writes WAV with filename pattern `<source>_<YYYYMMDDTHHMMSSZ>_<arc>_<sampleid>.wav`<br/>- WAV is 24-bit PCM, 48 kHz, peak-normalized to -1 dBFS unless `peak < -30 dBFS` in which case raw is preserved<br/>- record inserted into `index.sqlite` with `gain_db` set to the normalization adjustment<br/>- tests verify file presence, format (24/48), peak-normalize behavior, and DB row |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:107:| CCS-019 | Implement self-quotation loop: when a song completes with arc-payoff > threshold AND clicks=0, sample a 4-second window of `SuperCollider:out_1` for the next session. | MUST | T1 | - `tools/duet_composer.py` post-song hook calls `sample_capture_daemon::self_quote(score_summary)` when arc_payoff > 0.6 AND click_count == 0 AND mode != working_ambience<br/>- daemon captures from `SuperCollider:out_1` (via `system:capture_X` after a small JACK loopback connection it manages itself) the 4-second window centered on the moment of peak rolling_peak during the song<br/>- saves to `samples/self/` with `arc_phase`, `mood`, `mode`, and a `self_quote_source_song_id` extra tag<br/>- tests with a mock self-listener stream and arc-payoff fixture verify trigger condition, capture window, and tag propagation |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:108:| CCS-020 | Add systemd unit `cypherclaw-sample-capture.service` that runs `sample_capture_daemon.py` with `Restart=always`, dependent on `cypherclaw-jack.service`. | MUST | T2 | - unit file at `my-claw/systemd/cypherclaw-sample-capture.service`<br/>- `User=user`, `LimitMEMLOCK=infinity`, `ExecStart=/home/user/cypherclaw/.venv/bin/python3 /home/user/cypherclaw/tools/sample_capture_daemon.py`<br/>- `After=cypherclaw-jack.service`, `Requires=cypherclaw-jack.service`<br/>- enabled on boot via `cypherclaw_boot.sh`<br/>- daemon survives a 30-minute soak test with simulated JACK xruns |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:109:| CCS-021 | Implement TDD-grade test fixtures with canned 1-second audio windows representing each detector branch (silence, footsteps, dishwasher, music, dogs, transient cluster) for fast deterministic CI. | MUST | T1 | - `my-claw/tests/fixtures/sample_capture/` directory with WAV fixtures<br/>- `test_sample_capture_daemon.py` exercises each fixture against the detector and asserts expected flag<br/>- fixtures are short (≤2 s) and committed to repo so CI does not need real JACK<br/>- documented as the way to add new detector cases |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-cypherclaw-sampler.md:112:| CCS-024 | When a human plays the MIDI keyboard or Theramini for >5 seconds during a song, capture that input phrase to `samples/keyboard/` or `samples/theramini/` with full tagging. | MUST | T1 | - `sample_capture_daemon.py` listens for keyboard/theramini activity via existing state files (`/tmp/midi_keyboard_activity.json`, `/tmp/theramini_state.json`)<br/>- on >5-second sustained play, captures the corresponding window from the appropriate JACK input<br/>- tags include `human_player` (e.g. `anthony` if face_recognition supports it, else `unknown`), `instrument` (`midi_keyboard` / `theramini`), and the inferred key the human played in<br/>- tests verify trigger threshold, source routing, and tag inclusion |\n++tests/test_daemon_fallback.py:126:    def test_child_process_env_strips_systemd_watchdog_vars(\n++tests/test_daemon_fallback.py:535:        monkeypatch.setattr(cypherclaw_daemon, \"_runner_service_state\", lambda: \"active\")\n++tests/test_daemon_fallback.py:601:        monkeypatch.setattr(cypherclaw_daemon, \"_runner_service_state\", lambda: \"inactive\")\n++tests/test_daemon_fallback.py:1035:        monkeypatch.setattr(cypherclaw_daemon, \"_runner_service_state\", lambda: \"active\")\n++tests/test_daemon_fallback.py:1114:        monkeypatch.setattr(cypherclaw_daemon, \"_runner_service_state\", lambda: \"inactive\")\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-model-awareness.md:40:| REQ-014 | Set TMPDIR and Claude cache paths to tmpfs (/run/cypherclaw-tmp) in the systemd service environment so agent disk writes go to RAM | MUST | T1 | Agent processes write temp files to tmpfs, verified by lsof during agent execution |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:7:This PRD turns that incident into immediate operational work. The goal is not \"better backups\" in the abstract. The goal is that a clean reboot, an I/O-guard intervention, or a single-service crash must never again destroy or materially rewind the authoritative queue.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:13:3. Every important process is systemd-managed.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:23:2. **Process authority** — the daemon and runner must start, stop, and recover through systemd rather than ad hoc shell sessions.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:50:2. **No critical process runs outside systemd.**\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:88:- Daemon service: `cypherclaw.service`\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:98:| HOME-005 | Add a preflight validator. Create `tools/preflight.py` that validates DB integrity, service prerequisites, queue sanity, lock-file sanity, and backup freshness before allowing the runner to start. | MUST | T1 | - Fails closed on invalid DB or missing dependencies<br/>- Detects orphaned lock files and stale tmpfs state<br/>- Emits machine-readable and human-readable output |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:99:| HOME-006 | Create `cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service` and move `sdp-cli run` under systemd. The queue runner must no longer rely on `nohup`, ad hoc shells, or manual restart. | MUST | T1 | - Runner starts via `systemctl start cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service`<br/>- `Restart=always` is enabled so clean `sdp-cli run` exits do not leave the queue dead<br/>- Maintenance-mode launcher exits do not restart-loop (`SuccessExitStatus=75`, `RestartPreventExitStatus=75`)<br/>- Logs are journaled and visible without tailing a custom shell log<br/>- Reboot restores runner under ordered startup |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:100:| HOME-007 | Create a dedicated bootstrap layer for tmpfs and workdir prep. Add `cypherclaw-bootstrap.service` to initialize caches, workdirs, and symlinks without owning the authority DBs. | MUST | T1 | - Bootstrap runs before daemon and runner<br/>- tmpfs directories exist after boot<br/>- bootstrap is idempotent<br/>- bootstrap never downgrades live DB state |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:102:| HOME-009 | Create `tools/safe_reboot.sh` to perform checkpoint, maintenance-mode drain, service shutdown, reboot, post-boot validation, and resume. | MUST | T2 | - Script checkpoints before reboot<br/>- Stops services in a defined order<br/>- Verifies post-boot counts against checkpoint manifest<br/>- Refuses to resume runner if validation fails |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:104:| HOME-011 | Remove hardcoded operational secrets from scripts and unit files. API keys and bot tokens must come from environment files or a secret store, not inline shell variables. | MUST | T1 | - No hardcoded Telegram bot token in `io_guard.sh`<br/>- No hardcoded model/API secret in systemd unit files<br/>- Secret source is documented and permission-scoped |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:119:4. **HOME-006** — create `cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service`.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:120:5. **HOME-007** — split bootstrap into a real pre-start service.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:140:4. Create `systemd/cypherclaw-sdp-runner.service`.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:141:5. Create `systemd/cypherclaw-bootstrap.service`.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:162:Runner and bootstrap must become explicit services with a maintenance gate.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:172:The system must degrade gracefully under I/O or service distress and report what it is doing.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:186:| Runner restart path | 100% systemd-managed |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-home-resilience.md:196:2. A runner crash restarts under systemd after passing preflight.\n++tests/test_cypherclaw_boot_runtime.py:27:    assert \"cypherclaw-observer-ollama.service\" in script\n++tests/test_cypherclaw_boot_runtime.py:55:def test_observer_ollama_service_runs_on_dedicated_port_as_ollama() -> None:\n++tests/test_cypherclaw_boot_runtime.py:56:    unit = (ROOT / \"my-claw\" / \"systemd\" / \"cypherclaw-observer-ollama.service\").read_text()\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-local-llm-integration.md:48:| LLM-002 | Configure Ollama for multi-model serving. Set environment variables in Ollama's systemd service: `OLLAMA_MAX_LOADED_MODELS=3`, `OLLAMA_KEEP_ALIVE=30m`, `OLLAMA_FLASH_ATTENTION=1`, `OLLAMA_KV_CACHE_TYPE=q8_0`, `OLLAMA_NUM_PARALLEL=1`. Verify Ollama uses mlock to keep loaded models in RAM (default behavior). Set CPU governor to performance mode. | MUST | T1 | - Ollama systemd override created with all env vars<br/>- `ollama ps` shows 3 models loaded simultaneously<br/>- CPU governor set to performance<br/>- mlock verified via `cat /proc/<pid>/status \\| grep VmLck` |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-local-llm-integration.md:50:| LLM-004 | Install and configure llamafile as a dedicated classification server. Download the llamafile binary and Qwen3.5-4B GGUF file. Create a systemd service `cypherclaw-router.service` that runs llamafile on port 8081 with 4 reserved threads, 2048 context size, and JSON grammar constraint. The service should start after Ollama, restart on failure, and use ionice/nice to limit I/O priority. | MUST | T2 | - llamafile binary installed at `/usr/local/bin/llamafile`<br/>- GGUF model file stored at `/home/user/models/qwen3.5-4b-q4_k_m.gguf`<br/>- systemd service created and enabled<br/>- Server responds on port 8081 to OpenAI-compatible API<br/>- JSON output validated<br/>- Test classification returns in <200ms |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-local-llm-integration.md:57:| LLM-011 | Create Ollama health monitoring. Add Ollama status to the I/O watchdog: check that Ollama is running, which models are loaded, memory usage per model. If Ollama becomes unresponsive, restart it via systemd. Add Ollama metrics to the Redis metrics store: loaded_models, total_model_ram, ollama_responsive. Show Ollama status in `/health` command output. | MUST | T1 | - Watchdog checks Ollama health every 30s<br/>- Auto-restart on unresponsive Ollama<br/>- Ollama metrics in Redis<br/>- `/health` shows loaded models and Ollama RAM usage<br/>- llamafile health also monitored |\n++my-claw/sdp/execution-roadmap.md:25:| 2 | [prd-restructure.md](./prd-restructure.md) | Stable imports, packaging, service paths | Reliable installs, cloneability, reusable services |\n++my-claw/sdp/execution-roadmap.md:32:| 8 | [prd-pet-system-v2.md](./prd-pet-system-v2.md) | Pet/personality depth in service of the organism | Stronger identity continuity |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-gallery-display.md:17:5. **Graceful degradation** — if no monitor detected, service does not start; if framebuffer unavailable, falls back to ANSI-only\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-gallery-display.md:78:| GD-013 | Systemd service with monitor detection | MUST | T3 | - Service unit with `ConditionPathExists=/dev/fb0` - `After=cypherclaw.service` dependency - `TTYPath=/dev/tty1`, `StandardInput=tty` - `Restart=on-failure` with 10s delay - Does not start if no monitor/framebuffer detected |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-gallery-display.md:81:| GD-016 | Screen blanking prevention | MUST | T1 | - Disables console screen blanking (`setterm -blank 0 -powerdown 0`) - Disables DPMS power saving on tty1 - Resets on service stop to restore defaults |\n++tests/test_sample_capture_verify.py:1:\"\"\"Tests for sample_capture_verify smoke-test entry point.\"\"\"\n++tests/test_sample_capture_verify.py:14:from sample_capture_verify import (\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-capability-approval-framework.md:5:CypherClaw already behaves as if some actions are low-risk and some require caution, but the boundaries are still scattered across prompts, heuristics, and human convention. That is workable for a prototype, but not for a long-running artistic home that modifies code, restarts services, and operates unattended.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-capability-approval-framework.md:24:   Read, write, exec, network, deploy, db, service-control, and destructive actions must be modeled directly.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-capability-approval-framework.md:42:| CAF-001 | Create a capability registry module that classifies actions and tools into explicit classes: `read`, `write`, `exec`, `network`, `deploy`, `db`, `service_control`, `destructive`. | MUST | T1 | - Registry exists and is importable<br/>- Core tool and action types are mapped to capability classes<br/>- New actions can be added without editing prompts |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-restructure.md:55:If the import graph and packaging stay unstable, every later agent, verifier, and service task inherits avoidable failure modes.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-restructure.md:93:| RS-004 | Update the systemd service file to reference the new daemon path. Change `ExecStart` from `tools/cypherclaw_daemon.py` to either `python3 -m cypherclaw.daemon` or the new `src/cypherclaw/daemon.py` path. Ensure the daemon starts correctly after the change. | MUST | T1 | - systemd service updated<br/>- `sudo systemctl daemon-reload`<br/>- `sudo systemctl restart cypherclaw` succeeds<br/>- Daemon starts and responds to Telegram |\n++my-claw/sdp/task-audit-20260402.md:94:7. Resume deeper `GlyphWeave Art Studio`, `Narrative Engine`, and `Pet System v2` work in service of the embodied organism.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-verification-system.md:38:| **High** | Code commits, file modifications, config changes, PR creation, service restarts, deployments, database modifications | Full lead/verify/fix cycle BEFORE action | 1-5 minutes |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-verification-system.md:45:| VER-001 | Create `tools/risk_classifier.py` that classifies every action into risk levels (none/low/medium/high/critical). Classification uses: (a) action type (reply, code_change, shell_command, deployment, config_change), (b) target (own codebase, production server, external service, other people's repos), (c) lead agent's self-rated confidence (parsed from response metadata or estimated from response length/complexity), (d) category matching (technical advice, code snippets, and file references → medium; commits and restarts → high). Classification is local (no LLM call) using keyword matching and rule engine. | MUST | T2 | - All 5 risk levels assignable<br/>- Classification runs in <10ms (no LLM call)<br/>- Action type detection works for all daemon step types<br/>- Confidence estimation from response characteristics<br/>- Category matching for technical content<br/>- Classification logged to Observatory |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-gap-analyzer.md:17:1. **Three gap categories** — code gaps (missing files, broken imports), infrastructure gaps (services down, packages missing, config drift), integration gaps (modules exist but aren't wired together)\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-gap-analyzer.md:19:3. **Auto-fix simple gaps** immediately (missing packages, file sync, service restart), create sdp-cli tasks for complex gaps (new code needed, integration work)\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-gap-analyzer.md:31:├── infra_scanner.py               # Infrastructure gap detection — services, packages, config\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-gap-analyzer.md:46:| GA-003 | Create `gap_analyzer/infra_scanner.py` — verify infrastructure state matches expectations: (1) all systemd services running (cypherclaw-daemon, cypherclaw-gallery, redis, ollama, nginx), (2) all venv packages installed in BOTH main and workdir venvs, (3) workdir in sync with main codebase (no files in main missing from workdir), (4) all database files exist and are valid SQLite, (5) Ollama models loaded, (6) disk/tmpfs space adequate. | T2 |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-gap-analyzer.md:50:| GA-007 | Create `gap_analyzer/e2e_runner.py` — per-PRD end-to-end integration tests. For each PRD, define a smoke test that exercises the full workflow: (1) Art Studio: call art_engine.generate_art() and verify output file exists in gallery/renders/. (2) Pet System: create a pet, feed it, check stats update. (3) Gallery: verify service running, art directory has files, framebuffer accessible. (4) Narrative Engine: instantiate engine, verify world state DB created. Tests use real local resources (Ollama, SQLite) but mock external APIs (Telegram, cloud agents). | T2 |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-gap-analyzer.md:52:| GA-009 | Create `gap_analyzer/auto_fixer.py` — immediately fix simple gaps without creating tasks: (1) missing venv package -> pip install, (2) file not synced to workdir -> cp, (3) service not running -> systemctl restart, (4) stale lock file -> rm, (5) missing directory -> mkdir. Log all auto-fixes. Complex gaps (missing code, broken integration) -> create sdp-cli tasks automatically. | T2 |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-glyphweave-art-studio.md:77:| GW-008 | Create the gallery web server at `tools/art_gallery/` using FastAPI + HTMX + Jinja2 templates. Pages: (1) Gallery grid — all artworks as thumbnails with composite score overlay, filterable by model, art_type, score range, date, pet, theme; sortable by score, date, recency. (2) Artwork detail — full-size render, text version in code block, AEAF player for animations, generation stats (model, effort, time, retries), assessment scores radar chart, qualitative feedback. (3) Experiment dashboard — calibration progress, model leaderboard table, score distributions per model (box plots), generation time comparison, success rate heatmap (model × art_type). (4) Live canvas — prompt input, model/effort/size/palette selectors, generate button, real-time status, result display with scores. (5) Remix — take existing artwork, modify parameters, regenerate. Serve static files (rendered PNGs) from disk. Run as a systemd service on port 8080, accessible via Tailscale. | MUST | T3 | - Gallery grid loads with thumbnail images and scores<br/>- Filtering by model, art_type, score, date works<br/>- Detail page shows PNG, text, scores, generation stats<br/>- AEAF animations play in browser (JS frame player)<br/>- Experiment dashboard shows calibration progress and leaderboard<br/>- Live canvas generates art on demand and displays result<br/>- Remix modifies parameters and regenerates<br/>- Server runs on port 8080 as systemd service |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-glyphweave-art-studio.md:86:| GW-017 | Create a systemd service for the gallery web server at `/etc/systemd/system/cypherclaw-gallery.service`. The service should: run as user `user`, start after postgresql and cypherclaw services, use the same TMPDIR and environment as the daemon, restart on failure with 10-second delay, bind to port 8080. Add an Nginx reverse proxy config to serve the gallery at a clean URL if Nginx is available. | SHOULD | T1 | - Service file created and enabled<br/>- Gallery starts on boot after postgresql<br/>- Gallery accessible at cypherclaw:8080<br/>- Service restarts automatically on crash<br/>- Logs go to journalctl |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-glyphweave-art-studio.md:106:Build the web gallery, Telegram buttons, systemd service, and `/art` commands. Full interactive experience.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-authoring-rules.md:23:- one service or daemon path\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-authoring-rules.md:153:- all services restart cleanly\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-authoring-rules.md:235:If you cannot point to the main file, service, schema, or display path that owns the row, the row is probably too broad.\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-clone-and-home-creation.md:30:| HOMECLONE-003 | Package the service bootstrap payload for release-snapshot installs. | MUST | T2 | - Bootstrap payload includes service templates for a clean target<br/>- Services can be configured from installer artifacts alone<br/>- Payload contents match the manifest |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-clone-and-home-creation.md:33:| HOMECLONE-005 | Add an unattended service/bootstrap step that configures the new home from the installer payload and starts the managed services. | MUST | T2 | - Managed services start from the installed payload<br/>- Bootstrap uses installer artifacts rather than local repo assumptions<br/>- Failed bootstrap leaves a readable report |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-clone-and-home-creation.md:38:| HOMECLONE-010 | Add a post-install verification step that checks service health, authority DB locations, write permissions, and queue readiness before the new home is considered live. | MUST | T1 | - Failed verification keeps the home in a not-live state<br/>- Verification report is machine-readable and human-readable<br/>- Success records a live-home activation event |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-clone-and-home-creation.md:41:| HOMECLONE-013 | Add end-to-end tests covering unattended install, clone install, standalone install, federated install, and idempotent reinstall behavior. | MUST | T2 | - Test matrix covers all install modes<br/>- Clone tests verify inherited state + empty queue<br/>- Reinstall tests prove no duplicate identities or broken services |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-web-platform.md:11:**Depends on:** `prd-home-resilience.md` (durable services and reboot-safe state), `prd-restructure.md` (stable package layout), `prd-agent-runtime-substrate.md` (real-time execution stream), `prd-context-engine.md` (session briefs and compacted context), `prd-verification-system.md` (safe action routing), `prd-model-awareness.md` (provider/model telemetry), `prd-glyphweave-art-studio.md` (gallery absorbed into platform), `prd-pet-system-v2.md` (pet data for virtual room), `prd-server-optimization.md` (status dashboard data), `prd-local-llm-integration.md` (local model status)\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-web-platform.md:57:| WEB-001 | Set up the FastAPI backend at `tools/web/backend/`. Serve Vue.js SPA as static files. WebSocket endpoint at `/ws` for real-time updates. REST API at `/api/`. Use uvicorn with auto-reload in dev, gunicorn in production. Create systemd service `cypherclaw-web.service` on port 3000. Nginx proxies from port 80/443 to 3000. | MUST | T2 | - FastAPI server starts and serves SPA<br/>- WebSocket connects at /ws<br/>- REST API responds at /api/health<br/>- systemd service created and enabled<br/>- Nginx proxy configured<br/>- Accessible via Tailscale at cypherclaw.tail*.ts.net |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-web-platform.md:67:| WEB-011 | Implement PWA support. Add a web manifest (`manifest.json`) with CypherClaw icon, theme color (dark), display mode (standalone). Add a service worker for: offline caching of static assets, background sync for chat messages sent while offline, push notification registration. Push notifications for: I/O guard alerts, task completions, pet evolution events, art generation complete. Use Web Push API with VAPID keys. | SHOULD | T2 | - Manifest allows \"Add to Home Screen\" on mobile<br/>- App opens in standalone mode (no browser chrome)<br/>- Static assets cached for offline access<br/>- Push notifications delivered for key events<br/>- Works on iOS Safari and Android Chrome |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-web-platform.md:109:| Uptime | >99% (systemd auto-restart) |\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-synthesis-and-orchestration.md:344:Implement `engine.py`. The tree of Oscillators from arc root to sample leaves. Main loop: read sensors → update organism moods → update arc position → evaluate section stability → generate phrases for active voices → render Oscillator tree to audio buffer → output to ALSA playback channels. The engine IS the recursive pattern — one loop tick evaluates every Oscillator at its appropriate rate. Integrates all components. Runs as daemon within embodiment service, replacing current `ambient_engine.py`. Graceful startup (fade in over 30 seconds) and shutdown (fade out over 10 seconds). Write integration tests verifying end-to-end audio output.\n++tests/test_emsd_performance.py:39:    assert adjustment.sample_capture_path.endswith(\"room_capture.wav\")\n++my-claw/sdp/prd-proactive-i